	<descriptions>
		<description descriptionType="Abstract">Along the Galápagos Spreading Center 3He/4He varies from 8.5 to 5.9 RA. High 3He/4He ratios, resembling those in the western and southern Galápagos islands, are absent. The most striking feature is a 3He/4He gradient, decreasing westward from 8.4 to 7.0 RA between 89° and 93°W, where the GSC is shallowest and shows “axial high” morphology. </description>
		<description descriptionType="Other">Related publications: Graham, D. W., B. B. Hanan, J. E. Lupton, K. Hoernle, R. Werner, D. M. Christie and J. M. Sinton  (2014) "Helium isotope variations and mantle plume – spreading ridge interactions along the Galápagos Spreading Center." Geophysical Monograph 204. The Galápagos: A Natural Laboratory for the Earth Sciences. Eds. K. S. Harpp, E. Mittelstaedt, N. d’Ozouville and D. W. Graham, pp. 391-412.</description>
	</descriptions>
